 Ground]] | Chislehurst won by 5 wkts | align="right" | <ref name=CS21>Waghorn, p. 21.</ref><ref name=ACS20/> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | London scored less than 100 in their combined innings. Chislehurst had scored 73 in the first innings and won "without much difficulty". |- | colspan="5" | |- | align="right" | 21 July (F) | [[Horsmonden Cricket Club|Horsmonden]] v [[Chislehurst Cricket Club|Chislehurst]] | [[Horsmonden]] | Horsmonden won by an innings and 4 runs | align="right" | <ref name=CS21/> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | The return match to the one at Chiselhurst on Tuesday, 11 July. Played for (again) "a considerable sum", it was won by Horsmonden "in one Hands (''sic''), all but 4 notches". The use of "hands" in this context means "[[innings]]", so Horsmonden achieved an innings victory, one of the earliest on record. |- | colspan="5" | |- | align="right" | 11 August (F) | [[London Cricket Club|London]] v [[Mitcham Cricket Club|Mitcham]] | [[Artillery Ground]] | London won by 1 wkt | align="right" | <ref>Buckley, p. 15.</ref><ref name=ACS20/> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | Mitcham totalled 117-20 in two innings; London 118-19 in two innings. Strangely, the only report of this was in the ''Warwickshire & Staffordshire Journal'' dated Thursday, 17 August. |- | colspan="5" | |- | align="right" | September | [[London Cricket Club|London]] v [[Chislehurst Cricket Club|Chislehurst]] | [[Artillery Ground]] | London won | align="right" | <ref>Waghorn, pp. 21–22.</ref><ref name=ACS20/> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | Betting on London at the start of the second innings was a [[guinea (British coin)|guinea]] to a [[shilling (British coin)|shilling]]. |- |}
==Other events== An advertisement in the ''[[Sherborne Mercury]]'' dated Tuesday, 9 May, is the earliest reference to cricket in [[Dorset]]. Twelve [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] men at Ridgway (''sic'') Races challenged twelve men from elsewhere to play them at cricket for the prize of twelve pairs of gloves valued at a [[Shilling (British coin)|shilling]] a pair.<ref name=JM116>Major, p. 116.</ref>
''September''. An inter-parish match in [[Sussex]] between teams from [[Eastbourne]] and [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle]]. [[Lord John Sackville]] captained Eastbourne, who won by 4 wickets.<ref name=CS21/>
