{{Infobox sports team | name = Nigeria bobsled team | logo = | logo_size = | alt = | caption = | sport = [[Bobsledding]] | founded = 2016 | league = [[International Bobsleigh and Skeleton Federation]] | conference = <!-- Pan-African federation --> | division = {{ubl |Federation: [[Bobsled and Skeleton Federation of Nigeria]] |Country: {{flag|Nigeria}} |NOC: {{flagIOC|NGR}} }} | city = | Chairman = [[Seun Adigun]] | managing_director = | coach = | manager = [[Seun Adigun]] | gm = | championships = | League_titles = | division_titles = | mascot = | fanclub = | broadcasters = | media = | uniforms = | members = {{ubl| | [[Seun Adigun]] | [[Ngozi Onwumere]] | [[Akuoma Omeoga]] }} | partners = | main_sponsor = | website = }} The '''Nigeria bobsled team''' or '''Nigerian bobsleigh team''', represents [[Nigeria]] in [[bobsledding]]. The first team was established in 2016 by [[Seun Adigun]], as a women's team for the 2-women event. In 2017, they qualified to be the first Nigerians at the Winter Olympics, and first Africans in bobsled at the Winter Olympics.<ref name=NYT-2018-03-06> {{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/01/31/magazine/winter-olympics-bobsled-nigerian-seun-adigun.html |title= The First African Team to Compete in Bobsled |author= Jaime Lowe |publisher= New York Times |date= 6 March 2018 }} </ref>
==History== The first national team was established in 2016 by [[Seun Adigun]], in [[2-Person Bobsled|2-woman bobsleigh]]. The team was entirely self-funding, without financial support from Nigerian authorities. Raising the money to run the team showed the Nigerian government that they needed to establish a governing federation for bobsled, which they did, the [[Bobsled & Skeleton Federation of Nigeria]] (BSFN). The team's first attempt to qualify for the [[Winter Olympics]], was in 2017, for the [[2018 Winter Olympics]] in [[Bobsleigh at the 2018 Winter Olympics|bobsledding]], the [[Bobsleigh at the 2018 Winter Olympics – Two-woman|two-women]] event. The 2018 Olympic team consisted of driver [[Seun Adigun]], and brakemen [[Ngozi Onwumere]] and [[Akuoma Omeoga]]. In November 2017, the team met the basic standard to participate in the qualifications. If the team qualifies, this would represent the first appearance of [[Nigeria at the Olympics|Nigeria]] at the Winter Olympics; and the first African team in bobsled. The team qualified for the Olympics, being [[Nigeria at the 2018 Winter Olympics|its representatives at the Winter Games]]. Nigeria became one of eight African countries to be represented at the 2018 Winter Olympics.<ref name=ABCau-2017-11-17> {{cite news |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-11-17/nigerias-bobsled-team-off-to-winter-olympics/9163162 |title= Nigerian bobsled team will be country's first-ever Winter Olympics representatives |date= 17 November 2017 |publisher= ABC News (Australia) }} </ref><ref> {{cite episode |airdate= 16 November 2017 |network= CTV |series= CTV National News }} </ref><ref name=CBC-2017-11-17> {{cite news |url= http://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/winter/bobsleigh/nigerian-womens-bobsled-team-olympics-1.4405884 |title= Nigerian women's bobsleigh team hope to make history in Pyeongchang |author= Wendy-Anne Clarke |date= 17 November 2017 |publisher= CBC News }} </ref><ref name=WashPost-2017-11-17> {{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/11/17/nigerian-women-become-first-african-bobsled-team-to-qualify-for-olympics/?tid=sm_tw |title= Nigerian women become first African bobsled team to qualify for Olympics |author= Marissa Payne |date= 17 November 2017 |publisher= Washington Post }} </ref><ref name=NPR-2018-02-20> {{cite news |author= Linus Unah |title= So How Excited Is Nigeria About Its History-Making Women's Bobsled Team? |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2018/02/20/587252058/so-how-excited-is-nigeria-about-its-history-making-womens-bobsled-team |date= 20 February 2018 |publisher= NPR }} </ref> Onwumere carried the Nigerian flag at the [[2018 Winter Olympics opening ceremony]] [[2018 Winter Olympics Parade of Nations|Parade of Nations]], and marched with her two teammates, along with fellow Nigerian [[Simidele Adeagbo]], who qualified for women's skeleton.<ref name=Time-2018-02-10> {{cite news |url= http://time.com/5142773/nigerian-bobsled-team-opening-ceremony-winter-olympics-2018/ |author= Jennifer Calfas |title= Nigeria’s First-Ever Bobsled Team Has Arrived at the Winter Olympics Opening Ceremony and People Are Really Excited |date= 10 February 2018 |publisher= Time Magazine }} </ref> The team finished last among the 20 teams who competed.<ref name=HoustonChronicle-2018-03-22> {{cite news |url= https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/texas-sports-nation/article/As-one-journey-ends-another-begins-for-Nigerian-12773995.php |title= As one journey ends, another begins for Nigerian bobsledders |author= Melanie Hauser |date= 22 March 2018 |publisher= Houston Chronicle }} </ref> After the Games, the 3 on the team retired from bobsled, but pledged to develop the sport in Nigeria, grow the Nigerian sporting federation, and grow winter sports and the Winter Olympics in Africa.<ref name=HoustonChronicle-2018-03-22/>
The team arrived in Nigeria to celebrate their Olympic experience in March 2018, organized by the BSFN marketing team, the Temple Management Company (TMC), starting at Murtala Mohammed International Airport (MMIA) Ikeja Lagos.<ref name=BellaNaija-2018-03-03> {{cite news |url= https://www.bellanaija.com/2018/03/nigerias-bobsled-team-arrives-south-korea/ |title= Nigeria’s Bobsled Team arrives from South Korea |date= 3 March 2018 |publisher= Bella Naija }} </ref>
==Equipment== * ''Maeflower 1'', a training sled built out of wood, named after "Mae-Mae", Amezee Adigun, Suen Adigun's deceased sister.<ref name=WashPost-2018-02-20> {{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/if-you-want-to-celebrate-olympic-diversity-womens-bobsled-is-a-good-place-to-be/2018/02/20/e2bfa3f2-1603-11e8-b681-2d4d462a1921_story.html |title= If you want to celebrate Olympic diversity, women’s bobsled is a good place to be |author= Jerry Brewer |date= 20 February 2018 |publisher= Washington Post }} </ref> * ''Maeflower 2'', the team's first racing sled, which accompanied them to the 2018 Olympics.<ref name=WashPost-2018-02-20/>
