{{unreferenced|date=May 2017}} {{Motorsport venue| Name = Pyynikki Circuit | Location = [[Tampere]], [[Finland]] | Time = | Image = | Events = | Length_km = 3.608 | Length_mi = 2.242 | Turns = 11 (7 right, 4 left)| Record_time = | Record_driver = | Record_team = | Record_year = | }} The '''Pyynikki Circuit''' or '''Tampere Circuit''' is a former [[street circuit]] in [[Tampere]], [[Finland]]. The circuit was a {{convert|3.608|km|sigfig=4}} long clockwise circuit in a park (or on public streets) in the district of [[Pyynikki]]. The roadraces were known as "Pyynikinajot" and were first run from 1932-1939. After an interruption caused by the [[Second World War]] they were revived in 1946, running until 1971.
For the [[1962 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|1962]] and [[1963 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|1963]] seasons the [[Finnish motorcycle Grand Prix|Finnish Motorcycle Grand Prix]], a round of the [[Grand Prix motorcycle racing]] world championship, was held on the Pyynikki Circuit. The circuit was found to be too narrow, and therefore the Finnish Grand Prix was moved to the [[Imatra Circuit]] from [[1964 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|1964]].
Races on the Pyynikki Circuit were banned in 1971 for safety reasons, but in the final year the future [[List of Grand Prix motorcycle racing World champions|World Champion]] [[Jarno Saarinen]] won two classes.
