{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} {{Use British English|date=March 2016}} {{Infobox cricketer | name = Richard Edmeads | image = | country = England | fullname = Richard Edmeads | nickname = | birth_date = c.1740 | birth_place = [[England]] | batting = unknown hand | bowling = underarm: unknown hand and type | role = batsman | club1 = [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] | year1 = c.1761–1770 | club2 = [[Chertsey Cricket Club|Chertsey]] | year2 = c.1761–1770 | date = 18 March | year = 2013 | columns = 0 | source = [[H. T. Waghorn]] }}
'''Richard Edmeads''' (dates unknown) was an English [[Amateur status in first-class cricket#Distinction between amateurs and professionals|professional]] [[cricket]]er who played in [[first-class cricket]] for [[Chertsey Cricket Club]] and [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] during the 1760s. The brother of [[John Edmeads]], he is recorded in the Richmond v. Chertsey match on [[Richmond Green]] in September 1765. He and his brother shared 108 runs in the match which Chertsey won by 106 runs.<ref>Waghorn, p.59.</ref>
As Edmeads had established his reputation by 1765, he must have been active for some years previously and his career may have begun in the 1750s. He is not mentioned in 1770s reports although his brother continued to be a notable player in that decade. Very few players were mentioned by name in contemporary reports before the 1770s and there are no other references to Richard Edmeads.
