The men's [[college basketball]] program of the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) was founded in 1920 and is known competitively as the [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA Bruins]]. The Bruins have won 11&nbsp;[[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Men's Division I Basketball Championships]], the most of any school.<ref name=top10>{{cite web |title=Top 10 Colleges to Produce NBA Pros |date=June 21, 2011 |url=http://www.realclearsports.com/lists/colleges_nba_draft/ucla_bruins.html |publisher=RealClearSports |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66OAqTEcG |archivedate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> UCLA players have been assigned [[jersey number]]s ranging from 0 to 78 in the team's history.<ref name=numbers>{{cite web |title=2011–12 UCLA Men's Basketball Media Guide |pages=116–118 |year=2011 |publisher=UCLA Athletic Department |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ucla/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/2011-12/misc_non_event/1112_MBB_MG_History.pdf |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64TGSXFxI |archivedate=January 5, 2012|ref=2011_ucla_history}}</ref> The school no longer issues 10 [[retired number]]s in honor of former players.<ref>{{cite news|title=UCLA great Walt Hazzard passes away|date=November 18, 2011|agency=Sports Network|work=FoxNews.com|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/11/18/ucla-great-walt-hazzard-passes-away/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rgGUqEg|archivedate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> To qualify, a player must have been a three-time [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|consensus All-American]], a consensus [[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|national player of the year]], or been inducted into the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]]. The retired numbers are displayed in the rafters of the Bruins' home arena, [[Pauley Pavilion]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hartman|first1=Steve|last2=Smith|first2=Matt "Money"|title=The Great Book of Los Angeles Sports Lists|year=2009|publisher=Running Press|page=203|isbn=0786748877|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ps5bFjaB5PsC&lpg=PA203&dq=%22pauley%20pavilion%22%20rafters&pg=PA203#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> UCLA's legendary coach [[John Wooden]] generally opposed having numbers retired.
==History== [[File:Lew Alcindor Kareem Abdul-Jabbar UCLA.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Lew Alcindor, now [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], on a reverse dunk in 1967.]] Numbers retired by UCLA were originally limited to three-time consensus All-Americans.<ref name=pucin>{{cite news|last=Pucin|first=Diane|title=The Guttiest Little Bruin|date=December 18, 2004|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/2004/dec/18/sports/sp-goodrich18|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rscVGEx|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> In 1990, [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], known as Lew Alcindor during his UCLA career, and [[Bill Walton]] were the first to have their numbers retired.<ref>{{cite news|title=UCLA Set to Retire Numbers of Jabbar, Walton, Meyers, Curry|date=January 23, 1990|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-01-23/sports/sp-800_1_bill-walton|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rjHK997|archivedate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> The ceremony was held in conjunction with the 25th anniversary of Pauley Pavilion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bonk|first=Thomas|title=No Ordinary Retirement Home|date=February 3, 1990|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1990-02-03/sports/sp-906_1_pauley-pavilion|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67ruiqC3p|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UCLA Set to Retire Numbers of Jabbar, Walton, Meyers, Curry|date=January 23, 1990|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-01-23/sports/sp-800_1_bill-walton|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rucuFxC|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Wooden valued team play over individual accolades, and he opposed retiring numbers.<ref name=pucin/><ref name=schudel>{{cite news|last=Schudel|first=Matt|title=Legendary UCLA basketball coach John Wooden, winner of 10 national titles, dies at 99|date=June 4, 2010|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/04/AR2010060405092_pf.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67ruYIYSk|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> "What about the fellows who wore that number before?" Wooden asked. "Didn't they contribute to the team?"<ref name=schudel/> Wooden did think highly of Abdul-Jabbar and Walton. "If such a thing can be deserved, it'd be Alcindor and Walton. But I don't think it would be anyone else," said Wooden.<ref name=kawakami>{{cite news|last=Kawakami|first=Tim|title=Irish Find Little Luck in First Big East Season|date=February 1, 1996|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1996-02-01/sports/sp-31045_1_big-east-basketball|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67saZZidc|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref>
UCLA in 1996 expanded the requirements for retiring numbers to include players who were consensus national players of the year.<ref name=pucin/> This allowed the jersey numbers of [[Walt Hazzard]] (No. 42), [[Sidney Wicks]] (35), [[Marques Johnson]] (54) and [[Ed O'Bannon]] (31) to be retired.<ref name=kawakami/> In 2004, UCLA also allowed players inducted into the Naismith Hall of Fame to be eligible, enabling the retirement of [[Gail Goodrich]]'s No. 25.<ref name=pucin/><ref>{{cite news|last=Dohn|first=Brian|title=GOODRICH'S PLACE CEMENTED FORMER BRUINS STAR'S NO. 25 JERSEY FINALLY WILL BE RETIRED|date=December 18, 2004|newspaper=Daily News (Los Angeles)|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-9063858.html|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Three Bruins were inducted into the Hall of Fame in 2012, and UCLA retired their numbers in 2013—[[Jamaal Wilkes]] (52), [[Reggie Miller]] (31), and [[Don Barksdale]] (11).<ref>{{cite news|title=Wilkes, Miller head Hall of Fame class|date=April 2, 2012|agency=Associated Press|work=FoxSportsWest.com|publisher=FOX Sports Interactive Media, LLC|url=http://www.foxsportswest.com/04/02/12/Wilkes-Miller-head-Hall-of-Fame-class/landing_highschool.html?blockID=700732|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67uABqrkC|archivedate=May 24, 2012}}</ref>
Eight of the players honored were members of NCAA championship teams,<ref>{{cite news|last=Raley|first=Dan|title=Plenty of space available at Hec Ed|date=January 21, 2009|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/article/Plenty-of-space-available-at-Hec-Ed-1298122.php|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rhmArR6|archivedate=May 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Condotta|first=Bob|title=Husky Men's Basketball Blog|date=January 21, 2009|newspaper=The Seattle Times|url=http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/huskyhoops/2009/01/21/who_else_should.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rif9zNH|archivedate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> and seven of the players were coached by Wooden.<ref name=raley>{{cite news|last=Raley|first=Dan|title=Pac-10 Notebook: Huskies to hang Roy's No. 3 with the best|date=January 20, 2009|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/article/Pac-10-Notebook-Huskies-to-hang-Roy-s-No-3-with-1297989.php#page-1|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67rg3gxbD|archivedate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> Although Hazzard's No. 42 was retired, he allowed [[Kevin Love]] (2007–2008) to wear it.<ref name=numbers/><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Shelley|title=Walt Hazzard lived for others|date=November 18, 2011|work=ESPNLosAngeles.com|url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/columns/story/_/id/7252892/ucla-great-walt-hazzard-lived-others|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67tI1GdeL|archivedate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Painter|first=Jill|title=UCLA BASKETBALL NOTEBOOK: WOODEN WON'T MAKE TRIP TO INDIANAPOLIS|date=March 28, 2006|newspaper=Daily News (Los Angeles)|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-143886229.html|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hoffarth|first=Tom|title=THE NUMBERS GAME FROM 00 TO 99, WHICH PLAYER WOULD YOU CHOOSE FOR THE ALL-TIME SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA ROSTER? NO.32 IS LIKELY TO BE HOTTEST DEBATE|date=October 14, 2007|newspaper=Daily News (Los Angeles)|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8911505.html|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Johnson's retired No. 54 was worn by his sons, [[Kris Johnson (basketball)|Kris]] (1994–1998) and Josiah (2001–2005).<ref name=numbers/><ref>{{cite news|last=Sondheimer|first=Eric|title=Johnson Has Game to Go With His Name at UCLA|date=November 1, 2000|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/2000/nov/01/sports/sp-45340|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67se1aoll|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref>
In addition, UCLA announced on November 22, 2014 that the number 42 would be retired across all university sports in honor of [[Jackie Robinson]], a four-sport star at UCLA who went on to a [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] career in [[Major League Baseball]] and broke that sport's [[Baseball color line|20th-century color line]]. While Robinson wore several different numbers while at the school from 1939 to 1941, the number 42 was chosen because it was the number he wore during his [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Dodgers]] career. The all-sports retirement had no effect on men's basketball since that number had already been retired for Hazzard; however, Robinson's 42 will be prominently displayed within all UCLA athletic venues, including Pauley Pavilion.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.uclabruins.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30500&ATCLID=209775149 |title=UCLA Honors Jackie Robinson by Retiring #42 Across All Sports |publisher=UCLA Athletics |date=November 22, 2014 |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref> {{clear}}
